Every time I come here, I feel as if I'm rubbing elbows with Ginsberg and Kerouac.  It's an experience both humbling and revelatory.  I've never felt more like there was so much to know and so much I didn't know than during my first visit here.  It was great.  We all should feel like that some time, you know?</Text>

< text>
They came to make a freight delivery to my business. When they got to my business they called me from the phone # my shipper put on the freight invoice (which was the wrong #)  They called my number and I guess found out that number was wrong. At that point, instead of calling the shipper to confirm the  number or even googling my business name, they tried to leave. It absolutely made no sense....why would they take my freight all the way back to distribution center when all they had to do was make a call (or two). The I found out why... they charge an extra fee to re-deliver. Don't make the mistake of getting UPS parcel confused with UPS freight.
At first I was absolutely astonished, till I tried contacting customer service. That proved to be a waste of an hours worth of my time.

This UPS Freight location does not deliver the level of service I have come to expect with UPS.  Ordered a large patio set from Costco and thought it would be a no brainer.  According to tracking the shipment made it to San Leandro quickly, then I was called to schedule a delivery date and window, no problem.  Then they called me back to let me know they couldn't make it and had to reschedule, fine.  Then they didn't show at all, called me back to reschedule for a third time.  Then I get a call that says the driver cannot safely reach my house - yes I live in the mountains, but I've had plenty of 24' bobtail trucks deliver stuff here, including a hot tub from Costco a couple months ago (not UPS).

Finally after several calls to scheduling and dispatch, with a varied amount of unprofessionalism and rudeness, to give them an alternate address that is easier to reach, I get a call from the driver that he says he cannot reach it and I must meet him 5 miles from my house...oh, and he only has 1 of the 5 boxes in the shipment.  So now I have to wait for them to reschedule the delivery of the additional 4 boxes (which I'm certain are sitting in their warehouse), try to convince them to take an alternate route so they can reach my house, hope this communication makes it from scheduling, to dispatch and to the driver.  And if all goes perfectly I can meet the driver down the road, try to cram 4 huge boxes of furniture into my wife's minivan to shuttle them to my house.

What I thought would be a no-brainer order from Costco for patio furniture has turned into a time-consuming fiasco.  Not that anybody will read this before ordering something UPS freight from Costo in the Bay Area, but at least they can come here after the fact and see that they were not alone!< /Text>

This is a fraudulent business. Do not believe or trust them.</Review>

< Review>
I've used these guys since I moved to California in the 90s when I was a student with a beat-up used Corolla. After I got to know him and trust him, I used to tell John before a long road trip, "Pretend I'm your daughter, look over my car, and make sure it's good to go" without worrying that he was going to make up fake repairs to charge me for.

John gave me advice about car buying which I took, even though it meant I wound up with free routine maintenance from the dealer for years. By the time that deal ended, I'd lost track of TAS (formerly Swedish Asian Auto Service). Googling "John and Steve great mechanics" didn't work. Finally, my 14-year Prius needed real maintenance, so in desperation I sat down with Google maps to try and remember where they were. So I found them again- thank GOODNESS.

I've been back at TAS for two years now, they've replaced the 15 year old battery on my Prius now that it's worn out, and at this rate I'll have this car until it qualifies for vintage plates.

Last week, with a sense of d√©j√† vu, I went to John to say, "I'm making the first long road trip/camping trip in over 20 years, so I can visit my parents without worrying about giving them coronavirus by staying in a hotel or flying on a plane. Look over my car and make sure I'm safe for the journey." He fixed the timing cap leak we've been putting off repairing for a few years, and a few other things too, and I *know* he was being generous on labor costs. I'm not a kid anymore, but I feel perfectly safe driving off across the desert in a 16 year old Prius, which I'm not sure I would otherwise.

TL;DR: These guys are honest and dependable. I've mostly mentioned John, because he's the guy who usually takes care of me, but everybody who works there is great. I'm writing this review as an unsolicited thank you, but really, this is a long overdue review for the business I have depended on the longest‚Ä¶ I was going to say since I moved to California, but come to think of it, I've depended on them longer than any business, ever. And I'm a persnickety Karen, so that's saying a lot. ;)</Review>

After asking me some questions, John's opinion, based upon his experience, was to reset the light, tighten the gas cap (which was loose), air up the tires, and evalute the car from there.

A week later the lights are still off and the car is running perfectly.

I am not sure most shops would offer this type of service and give you the genuine impression they care more about you then they do about their cash register.  John and his team have a long term approach to their shop and know happy customers equal a healthy business.

Take your car to SAAS!</text>< Pics>
None</Pics>

Having just moved to Santa Rosa and needing a hair cut, I chose Dolce Vita based on the reviews on Yelp. Initially, I was somewhat dismayed as I arrived on time for my online appointment. < Review>
There's a really nice view here on a sunny day, but the food is a hit or miss.

If you want a hit, stick with the Crab Roll. The roll is super buttery, and the crab was very fresh.
Comforting and delicious.

Tomato bisque was meh. Too watery. The croutons that come with it are better than the soup itself (lots of garlic & parmesan).

I would skip the fish & chips, or more accurately, the fish - it has too much batter and you can barely taste it.
The chips themselves are very actually: they're proper chips, crispy but meaty, potato wedges style, like they should be.< /Review>

< Review>
I have not reviewed any place since the pandemic started and to honest it is more difficult to review takeout places since this is new to many establishments and their food is best served in the restaurant. Takeout food  often loses quality during transportation. However, I must give a shout out to Fish. My hub and I are on the search (starting today ) for perfect fish and chips that are crisp, crunching and delicious. Fish did not disappoint. I figured that the drive home would ruin the meal and the crust and fries would be soggy and a mushy mess.  Well woo-hoo Fish have takeout fish and chips down to perfection. Crispy, favorable and if course of the highest quality. And as in the past, the staff are friendly, professional and engaging while still keeping distance.

So friends, it is worth the drive and cost during a time unlike we have experienced before. Happy New Year and stay well and well fed.< /Review>

< text>
Decided to go on a weekend trip to Sausalito and was looking for a place to eat. I was craving clam chowder and found this place. There was a line out the door and but the wait wasn‚Äôt that bad. My significant other and I decided to share an order of fish and chips and a cup of clam chowder. The clam chowder was a good thick consistency and was seasoned well. The fish and chips was definitely big enough for 2 people. We substituted the chips for shoelace fries and the fish sat on a sea of fries. The fish was nice and light but the batter was a bit too thick. Overall, I like this place but would try to order something else from the menu.<//text>

<review>ProTip: Order your to-go food ahead by calling the restaurant directly so by the time you arrive, you'll be ready to skip the long (weekend) lines and have your food ready. The outdoor patio in the restaurant proper is nice, but if too crowded, an even better view is from the mini park along the marina at the end of the parking lot.  Grab your to-go food, snag a bench by the water, and enjoy the experience!

If you've already ordered by calling ahead you can skip the line. Just walk right through the gate and look for the to-go pickup area. Pay (card accepted) and go.

Fish tacos and the dungeness crab roll are super fresh and tasty and make for easy waterside eating if you're grabbing a bench in the park.</review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN6PLPROSzG000oFlmCCJ5Ihu8PWIb7pv-Y-YM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><gmap_id>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13< /gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<Rating>3<//Rating>< text>
The white chowder is one of the best we've had.  It was wonderfully creamy with the broth made with bacon.   The clams were cleaned very well - we didn't taste any grit whatsoever.

Our salmon was beautifully presented with sprinkles of chives and pink Himalayan sea salt.   However it was a bit unevenly cooked and seasoned.

The po' boy sandwich was ok.  It was too soggy for our taste.  We also weren't impressed with the fish and chips.  They were a little dry.< /text>

Our favorite spot for a post hike reward. Amazing fish, great atmosphere, tons of outdoor seating. What more could you want? Feels like the only non touristy spot in Sausalito.

Highly recommend: salmon Saigon sando, tuna melt, market fish on greens, tuna poke appetizer, and the fish and chips. Really you can‚Äôt go wrong here.

The line might look long, but it moves quickly. Order at the counter and they bring it out very fast!< /Text>

<text>‚ÄúThe In-N-Out of FISH‚Äù -heard while waiting in line.

Tip: show up at opening to get a nice spot on the patio on a sunny day! Line starts forming well before opening.

My go-to is the tuna melt now that I‚Äôve been here 3 times, but looking forward to trying some of the other sandwich menu items like the ‚ÄúKorean KFC‚Äù cod sandwich and the cod Reuben. The tuna melt is excellent, by far the freshest tuna I‚Äôve had on a melt. The acme bread is delicious, and portions are huge; ratio of tuna to bread is literally like 3:1! Crab rolls and clams are all excellent as well.

<rating>3</rating><Gmap_id>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13</Gmap_id>< Date>
1502132339926<//Date>
< pics>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN4lYN_ztEkysrhQI02OiMAW9Z2UAC0wgDVHyY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>
<text>Went on a non holiday Sunday, decently sunny but not even a particularly nice day yet the line was out the door past the patio gate. Was with a friend who choose the place so we got in line and (somewhat) patiently waited.  And waited, and waited about 35 minutes just to order.

On top of that, the restrooms are around the back of the building, very small and horrifically maintained. (Was only ~3pm so not near closing)  In addition it is cash only so be prepared or use the ATM they have inside (3dollar fee).

I am all for sustainable, local food but I don't thrill this place was worth the cost, wait and drive out past downtown Sausalito.

They were out of halibut so the fish and chip we ordered used a lower quality fish (price was discounted to $21) they were crisp, 2 larger pieces and two smaller ones with a generous mound of chips (potatoes wedges) the fish was just way too saturated in oil, I tried dabbing a bit with a napkin but honestly it was just soaked through. The chips were less greasy, decently crisp on the outside but a bit mushy potato-y on the inside.
Must say, the tarter sauce was quite good though.

Also ordered the tuna melt, crunch outside of sand which, generous amounts of fish, but far too mushy and sausy, with too many capers- almost lost the sense of actual albacore and tuna.
Came with shoestring fries, a lot of them but rather than shoestring fries they were really the standard thickness.

Decent at first when they were warm but they got cold fast and then became extraordinarily hard, not crispy but just stale/hard.

I like the outdoor seating and general concept yet unfortunately the price was not worth the quality of food, and I felt a tad sick after, definitely needed a nap after only half the tuna melt and 1.5 pieces of the Fish chips due to the heavy amounts of grease.< /text>< user_name>
Javiera A. Sevilla<//user_name>

Mikhail Viznyuk</Name>
<date>1582071062895< /date>< Review>
They were out of the crab roll, so I went with their fish and chips and two specials: the local Dungeness crab and their steamed fish platter.

It is unfortunate that they were out of the crab roll since it looked like the best thing on their list, which is why I docked a star.

The fish and chips are phenomenal. The best I've had.

The Dungeness crab was fantastic as well, but a little pricey for what we got, since it was effectively just the crab plus some dry noodles on top for decoration. If I knew that, I would've bought an  additional entree.

Lastly, their fish platter special effectively was just mussels over potatoes, cabbage, etc. On realization, the platter was named after the restaurant and was misleading since it had zero fish.. in any case, it was really good and I enjoyed it, but it definitely took me for a whirl since I was expecting.. well.. fish.</Review>

<Rating>4</Rating>< Review>
We ordered the Portuguese Red Chowder - it's as delicious as the description. Well worth trying out if you're a chowder fan and really quite filling. It would be great if there were a gluten free alternative for the bread, but overall the meal was delicious. Note that the restuarant is in quite a popular area and it's quite likely you'll have to share a table. You order and pay first then find yourself a seat which isn't ideal for everyone.<//Review>

<userid>113059969585892968839<//userid>< Name>
Chris Kelley</Name>
< Time>
1535923144618< /Time>
<rate>4</rate>< Text>
They take credit cards now!
This place was great. Highly recommend getting there early, we were there 5min after they opened and waited in line maybe 5-8 minutes. When we left around 12:20 there was a line to the parking lot, probably a 25-30min wait.

Raw oysters were great, best I've had in the bay area. Had all three varieties they offered today and they were all delicious.

Crab roll was 10/10, my wife couldn't stop saying how good it was, she said it was the best she's ever had. Tons of meat, no mayo or anything just some butter and hella crab.

I had the Cod fish and chips, pretty standard fare but I was sharing with a 2 year old so had to stay conservative.

Staff was friendly, plenty of seating - outside is mostly community style tables, which I normally dislike but the vibe here makes it work.

Great little view of the harbor.

We will return, this place is a solid Sausalito option.< /Text>

Great place.   Prices seemed reasonable for the area. Unique walk-up/cash-only place. Halibut fish & chips were great as well as the Peacemaker fried oyster sandwich.   Being from New England the Halibut was a different taste and texture for fish & chips than we're re used to but it was not a mistake to order it. <Gmap_id>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13</Gmap_id><text>Workers were super cool. Food was delicious. Huge portions</text><username>Tony Nguyen< /username></record></dataset><record>
< review>
Reasonably Tasty, Highly Priced

I would echo a lot of the other reviews that I‚Äôve read (after eating here)‚Äîit‚Äôs good food, but it seems a little pricey.

I have no doubt that everything we ate was incredibly fresh, but over $70 for 3 lunches (and one beer) is a little rich for my wallet.  And the no cash rule seems a little anachronistic nowadays.

That being said, the sandwiches were large and very tasty.  However, I was disappointed with my Fish Tacos.  There were vary generous portions of grilled fish, however, they were so generous that they overwhelmed the small tortillas.  So, it was basically inedible as a taco‚Äîwhat I consider a ‚Äòhand meal‚Äô‚Äîand had to be eaten with a knife and fork.  For me, this spoils the flavor experience‚ÄîI ended up with a bunch of food all over my plate, without the nice balance of fish, cabbage, tortilla, sauce that I‚Äôd expect from a taco.  It seemed I ended up with a bite of each thing, one at a time.  So, larger tortillas, please!

Food was quickly prepared and delivered (you order at the counter, get a number, find a table).  There was a constant line of people, often 15-20 deep, but it seemed to flow pretty quickly.

It‚Äôs a great location, and a wonderful deck to sit and look at the boats and the bay, but to be honest, I‚Äôll explore other spots before I come back.</review>

The view and atmosphere of the restaurant are great. Paying only in cash is not, especially given the high prices on their food. I had the $17 tuna melt. I was expecting to be wowed by a tuna sandwich that expensive. Unfortunately, it was mushy and absolutely packed full of capers. I couldn't even taste the tuna. That many capers is just too much...geez. My husband had the $18 fish tacos. Tiny little corn tortillas with an even tinier serving of fish sitting on an enormous pile of dry cabbage. The red salsa it came with was delicious. I can appreciate the fact that everything was organic and the fish was sustainably caught. My daughter got Alfredo pasta which she really liked. Unfortunately, the high prices and cash only rule is a big drawback. Also, please use less capers in the tuna melt!!< /Text>

<user_name>Jason Karsh<//user_name></record></dataset><record>
<pictures>None<//pictures>< text>
Food way exceeded my expectations. Pricey, but the portions are huge, maybe big enough to share for two.

Pasta Con Vongole ($22): Homemade pasta. Clams overflowing. A very flavorful white wine sauce. Chile flakes for an added kick. Bliss.

Squid daily special: Shame this one isn't always available because it's fantastic. Had the option for getting it over salad or pasta and went with the pasta. Spicy and garlic aplenty for the sauce, but without the white wine from the pasta. Still great. The squid had an incredible wood BBQ'd flavor I've never experienced in squid before, I loved it.

White Chowder Bowl ($9 bowl): An all-around solid, classic bowl of New England chowder.

Pay the counter before you order, cash only.</text>

<user_name>Michelle Rowe</user_name>< resp>

<gmapID>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13</gmapID>< Text>
This spot is really amazing!
I came here on my bike after walking around Sausalito. It was recommended by my friend I was with and it did meet my expectations. We ordered the crab roll and it was delicious! So buttery! We got coleslaw with it, and I'm usually not a fan of coleslaw but I liked this one. It was a vinaigrette coleslaw instead of a mayonnaise based slaw. The bread they use for the roll was the perfect balance of crisp outer crust to soft center.
The inside is very laid back with benches to sit at and has a great coastal feel to it. There is plenty of outside seating too with heaters if it's a little on the chilly side.
I would have rated this place higher but they don't have a place to lock up your bike and it is cash only, so make sure you pull out at least $60 for dinner or lunch for two!<//Text>

<Rating>3< /Rating>< review>
This place has so much potential and I'd love to give it more stars, but it really shoots itself in the foot in some ways.

First of all, the good parts: the food is amazing, the parking is easy, and on a fair-weather day the deck is a wonderful place to eat.

Unfortunately, to experience this goodness, you first have to stand in line for half an hour or more and pay exorbitant prices ($25 for fish and chips!!) in CASH. It's 2017, people: what restaurant expects diners to pay $100+ for dinner and drinks in cash?? This one, apparently.<//review>

< Review>
This spot is really amazing!
I came here on my bike after walking around Sausalito. It was recommended by my friend I was with and it did meet my expectations. We ordered the crab roll and it was delicious! So buttery! We got coleslaw with it, and I'm usually not a fan of coleslaw but I liked this one. It was a vinaigrette coleslaw instead of a mayonnaise based slaw. The bread they use for the roll was the perfect balance of crisp outer crust to soft center.
The inside is very laid back with benches to sit at and has a great coastal feel to it. There is plenty of outside seating too with heaters if it's a little on the chilly side.
I would have rated this place higher but they don't have a place to lock up your bike and it is cash only, so make sure you pull out at least $60 for dinner or lunch for two!</Review>

<UserId.>106149036596342442791</UserId.><user_name>Ashi Vinod</user_name><date>1527453999660< /date>< rate>
3< /rate>
< text>
You can't go wrong with the view at the FISH restaurant.

We reached here at 11am and they don't begin serving the customers until 11.30am. The lines are out the door. I'm not kidding. This place was rated for best seafood on Michelin and yelp.

Based on the two reviews, people mentioned they only accept cash. Good news!! They have started to accept credit cards and they have ATM machine inside the restaurant too. They have plenty of sitting inside and outside.

And it's a kid friendly restaurant.

Food: we ordered fish and chips( Fish was fresh and cooked perfectly). It lacked flavors. The baked oysters were great but I left they were tiny. The Portuguese clam chowder was a little Salty. That was my least favorite.

Overall food is a little pricey. Fish and chips were  $21. 3 oysters for $9.

I don't mind coming back to try the rest of the menu.<//text>

<user>111356377455489648807</user><response>None< /response><gmap_id>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13<//gmap_id><date>1471011869937< /date><rating>5< /rating></record>
</dataset><record>
<user>101511678376615771710</user><name>Jason S< /name><date>1473036589587< /date><rating>5< /rating>< Review>
Fish.  Another instant favorite happened upon during a recent visit to the Bay Area.  It was a last-minute gamble discovered through Google Maps while standing at Battery Spencer early on a Friday evening.  I visited with a group of friends and we were all pleasantly surprised how perfectly this met our needs.  Apart from Fish, the marina area was essentially deserted - no cars, no people, it was wonderfully quiet and relaxed, right there on the waterfront.  I don't know if that is normal, but it was awesome.  Tons of available free parking - so simple.  What a great way to chill out after a big day.  The patio offers large, picnic table seating, so we had no problem gathering as a group of six for a laid-back, outdoor dinner.  I opted for the fish and chips with lemonade.  Yes. This was a good choice!  Plus, all of the (huge) salads and other items I saw people enjoying at other tables looked equally inviting.  As a huge bonus (for me), the speakers were calmly piping out lazy guitar blues - the mellow, Mississippi kind of stuff and other varieties (think Fred McDowell, John Hurt, Stefan Grossman and similar).  I *loved* this place!!  I will make an out-of-the-way effort to stop here again on any future trip into the area.  Not to be missed.< /Review>

<Rating>4</Rating>< review>
The food is 5-star, the ambiance is 4-star and because it's cash-only it's a 2-star for convenience in my book. I love the crab sandwich, and eating oysters at the rustic picnic benches overlooking the water. They also have great choices for wine and beer. Excellent spot to go if you're visiting Sausalito and want to get a feel for how this harbor town lives, eats and enjoys life.</review>

Rick Henrikson< /name>
<Time>1399860600407< /Time><Rate>3</Rate><review>A great place to go,
if you love standing in lines,
if not, save your time.

I usually don't write reviews until after I've eaten. However, I've been in line over an hour and have decided the quality of food can't possibly bring the rating beyond 3 stars. Inefficiency bugs me, and this place is a marvel of inefficiency. Giant line, cash only, and all seemingly intentional to give a show of being an old school dining experience. Hipsters without soul.

Pro tip: it took so long to get to the front that we ended up ordering take out. In spite of the fact that was asked the lady behind the bar about take out and she didn't tell us we can order there, it appears you actually can. < text>
To preface this review I hate crowds. Go early! I have been coming here since I was a kid and only locals new about this spot. It was childhood favorite over looking Sausalito Bay, now it is just overcrowded. There are more food options and they serve beer which is nice. It use to be more of a fish monger spot but now it is more of a tourist restaurant.

The food is good and I am glad that the fish is caught sustainably. I am just sad that it is so crowded. #gentrification</text>

< review>
Love the idea of sustainable seafood, but I was underwhelmed after my meal.  We had the white chowder, black cod (one of the fishes of the day), and the Saigon sandwich.  The chowder was good, but the sandwich was overly salty which was disappointing for costing $24 and the portion for the fish of the day was small.  The prices are a bit high to be cash only.  We arrived just before noon and there was about a 10-15 minute wait to place our order.  When we left just before 1pm, the line was 4 times as long.  So get there early if you can.</review>

<gmapID>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<Rating>5</Rating><username>Don V</username>< Review>
Wow this place is awesome. Casual restaurant, where you line up to order. Price is high, but worth it since the quality of the seafood is great.

We got the following
- Clam Chowder - ok, not a heavy clam chowder.
- Crab Roll - Amazing. lots of tender crab with a soft roll. This dish can be shared since it comes with a ton of shoestring fries.
- Ceviche - very good, has fresh fish and plenty of chips.

Seating outside is nice if the weather is good. You will have to get your own silverware etc, but its not a big deal. Price is high due to sustainable seafood, but in my opinion it's worth it.< /Review>

Pricy, but delicious!  I can't believe I ordered $38 Crab sandwich here. My friend highly recommended and sure enough, it was FANTASTIC.  You could easily taste that it was fresh and it wasn't smothered with any mayo, just organic butter and chives that accentuated the sweetness of the Dungeness crab. My mouth is watering as I type this. I don't plan on ordering again as it was expensive, but wanted to try once what a $38 crab sandwich would taste like!  I'm glad I walked away highly satisfied. Oh, and the portion was generous!<//text>

<Resp>None</Resp><user_id>114419215199559674940< /user_id>< text>
3.5 rounded to 4 stars. Long, long wait. But service is quick once you actually order. Clam dip was ok, chips served with it were not good but I had also ordered garlic bread and that was so much better with it. Garlic bread was delicious and dripping with butter.  Also tried both clam chowders. I have never had a red chowder before so I can't compare but it was pretty tasty but I barely had any clam in it! White chowder was just ok and was also low on clams.

Tried special salmon frame bits. I wasn't thrilled with that either but my friend really enjoyed it. Also tried my friend's albacore tuna from the tacos. Fish was so fresh!

Overall experience was just ok. Some hits and some misses. Also pretty pricey</text>

<user_id>104589054600774963024<//user_id>< username>
Andrew McMann</username>
<date>1341591173921</date><rate>3< /rate>< Review>
Typically Californian eco-aware cafe with but with a crusty old eastern seaboard dive ambiance interior. Most diners sit outside, at picnic tables on the large harbor side deck to take in the views, and salt air. The place is popular - there is often a long line of hungry folks (15 deep) willing to wait for the fresh, local fish served on any given day. (Open 7 days). The grilled catch of the day (wild salmon, farm raised  trout, black cod when we were there recently) grilled to order and served on a large mixed green salad or sandwich style. The ceviche was very good - with plenty of good sized chunks of white fish, lime juice, red onions, grapefruit, cilantro and avocado. The crab parfait was interesting - but the sweet pepper jelly layer made the whole concoction a tad too sweet. Fish and chips - we could really taste the beer in the beer batter. Fish tacos were very disappointing to the wife. Dry fish, disintegrating mini tortillas, mediocre salsa, no avocado.<//Review>

< Review>
It's very expensive, and the waits are very long. The views are fantastic and the food is good. They take only cash (there's an ATM on site). There seafood is locally sourced (the names of the boats that caught the fish are on the daily menu). We don't eat here any more, sadly, since they took the opportunity to put fois gras on the menu; it has nothing to do with their food, they did it just because they could.</Review>

< userid>
105603284385958429156</userid>
<Name>Rohenne Lee< /Name><Date>1462124453210</Date><Rating>4< /Rating><Review>If I could put 3.5 stars I would. The food was okay. Not as amazing as I expected from all the previous reviews.

Our first dish was the clam chowder, which was my favorite dish. They had another soup option that was tomato based, we also got that one but the taste had too much spices for my liking.

Second dish we got was a special of the day - baked clams. The clams were huge! Super chewy and fresh, but I think they tried to do too much with the taste. There was the basic lemon and salt and butter. But they added some seaweed and something else I couldn't quite figure out and that made the taste too complicated. This restaurant gets such fresh seafood that they should have just kept it simple and play out the freshness of the clams instead.

Last dish we got was the halibut fish n chips. The fish were perfectly fried. The batter tasted a bit sweet that it reminded me of donuts.

All in all, a great experience and a decent restaurant in Sausalito. The service was impeccable, the cashier who takes your order was very patient with everyone. Most people asked her about various items on the menu and what were her recs and she would repeat nicely what she's been saying to a lot of the people in line. Also the ambiance of the restaurant makes all the food taste a bit better especially if you sit on the patio. It's right next to the water and with nice weather, it'll make your experience that much better.< /Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><response>None<//response>< GmapID>
0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13</GmapID>
</record>

<gmap_id>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13</gmap_id><Date>1364314217075</Date><Resp>None</Resp><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< Review>
Was met by a huge line at 3:00 on a weekend, and almost left because of it. But the line goes fairly quickly, and once ordered, the food comes out very quickly. Sure you are paying a decent amount for fish and chips, but they are good, and you are eating them outside with beautiful views. We got a cup of ceviche, a bowl of guacamole and an order of fish and chips to share... more than enough for two people; we were stuffed. Some of the best ceviche and most generous portion I've had, would highly recommend. An Anchor Steam lager or a fresh Arnold Palmer goes nicely too.
Take a walk afterward and check out the houseboats: very cool.</Review>

<Text>I was disappointed all around by this restaurant. The location is excellent, there's good music playing, and the staff are reasonably friendly. This is where we go downhill: the food is not great. In the order that I consumed them: Clam Chowder. Ordered in a bowl, this clam chowder was WATERY. While it had chunks of potato and bacon, I did not see any clam whatsoever. It came from a large warmer just behind the counter. The cut of sourdough bread that accompanied it was burnt.The Shandy (Beer/Lemonade) was flat, first and foremost. This might have been saved by being mixed with a good lemonade, but the lemonade conveyed neither sweet nor tart taste. I could not finish it. The Rockfish sandwich was cooked thoroughly, and still agreeably juicy throughout, but had no flavor whatsoever and clearly had not been seasoned. The greens that came with it looked fresh, and tasted good, but we're not enough to save the bland filet. The tartar sauce is unimpressive as well. Awfully expensive for being so unimpressive at that.  I hope someone sees this and makes a change.< /Text><GmapID>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13<//GmapID>< response>

<user_name>Ian Green<//user_name></record></dataset><record>
<Time>1441251228916</Time><user>102751791041820450859<//user>< review>
CEVICHE ($14)
Generous portions of fish! I love it when the ceviche has more fish than "fillers" (aka onions). There were at least 3 types of fish and a perfect amount of chips to go with it. If I ever come back, I'll get the ceviche again.

FISH + CHIPS ($24 - omg)
I didn't eat this one but the price of this shocked me. There's three decently large pieces of fried fish with plain fries but I don't think I've ever paid over $15 for good fish and chips. Price definitely scared me away here.

We waited about 30 minutes in line to order at the cashier. The food came to the table pretty quickly though, so that's a winner.

Overall, pretty good place. Just a bit pricey.

CASH & CHECK (I know, how often does that happen?) ONLY.< /review>

Because I wanted to eat it, fish & chips ordered are also delicious with hokuhoku. Potatoes are fried fish and saltiness is just right. I always like to eat a little French fries, but here we get more and more hands. Fish is also delicious. Please attach a tartar sauce.
